        "paperTitleEnglish": "Regarding the formation of peer company communities and the possibility of development in the printing industry\n- Using Introduction of the company through interview analysis as a catalyst for the workshop -",
        "abstructEnglish": "With the recent advancement of digitalization, paper is rapidly disappearing. In this context, one of the industries that is beginning to decline is the printing industry. Furthermore, the gap between large corporations and small and medium-sized enterprises in Japan is widening year by year, becoming a social issue as a dual structure of the Japanese economy. The author, prompted by the high praise received for a paper book created in collaboration with several printing companies, came to believe that the possibility of the printing industry emerging from its path of decline might lie in the collaboration of multiple printing companies. This led to the implementation of this research. \n \n Based on the above background, this study aims to clarify the challenges faced by printing companies in small and medium-sized enterprises and explore the potential for creating new value through the formation of communities and collaboration among companies in the same industry.\n \n This study seeks to explore the causes of the decline in the printing industry beyond the reduction in demand for paper products due to digitalization. It will examine whether the printing industry can overcome its decline through collaboration among multiple companies working together to address these challenges.\n \n To test the hypothesis, methods such as interview surveys and workshops were employed. For the interview surveys, semi-structured interviews were conducted with multiple companies. Based on the insights gained from the interviews, workshops were designed and implemented with the aim of forming a collaborative community among companies. The workshops were conducted in multiple sessions and in a step-by-step manner, focusing on sharing issues among the participating companies and establishing common goals. In the initial workshop, company introductions based on interview analyses served as a starting point for community formation.\n \n One of the outcomes of this study was the successful formation of a community among the participants, which later developed into voluntary activities initiated by the participants themselves. Therefore, the effectiveness of aiming for collaborative solutions, rather than having small and medium-sized enterprises in the printing industry tackle challenges individually, was demonstrated. By developing this research further, the potential for the advancement of the printing industry through collaboration among multiple companies, including practical operations that take profits into account, is expected.\nExamination Committee",
